This recipe was absolutely scrumptious! We didn't have any peanuts, so we added 1/4 cup creamy peanut butter. It worked out perfectly! We didn't add the chocolate as well, but, WOW! were these cookies good! The dough was incredibly easy to work with, and tasted good too! A must make!

Rating: 4
I searched for a recipe to use up 10 bags of Planters peanuts I got on clearance at a store for 50 cents each. Since its summer it is way to early for peanut brittle. I really liked this cookie. It was very easy to make. I did drizzle the top with chocolate...yummm... definatly do not leave off. You do not have to grease the cookie sheets. I also refrigerated the dough in between batches which made it easy to work with. My cookies did spread out a lot. But it made the texture delicate and lacy. Definatly a cookie to make when your in a hurry.

Rating: 4
Very good, will definitely make again. This is a three fork recipe that gets a fourth fork for being so darn easy. As suggested, I used a couple tablespoons of peanut butter and instead used dark brown sugar as well as bittersweet chocolate on top (no butter). From start to finish, cookies were ready in under 30 min. Wow.

Rating: 3
I thought this was a good recipe, although not out of this world or anything. Also, the dough was too soft, as the batter spread out to form very large flat cookies. I added about 1/4 cup or so more flour and thought the consistency much improved. You'll also need to add some butter to the chocolate if you intend to drizzle it on top of the cookies (I did). Adding peanut butter to the cookie dough sounds like a good idea, too. All in all, a nice variation.

